<font color="#FF0000">MEDALS &amp; THE WAR</font><br>
<tt>Wed Feb 26 16:37:36 US/Eastern 1997
</tt><p>
Hey All-Fellow Vets and Doc:<br>
     Your most recent posts have brought back many memories and feelings.  In regards to medals and the war, I already explained how I felt, but here are so additional feelings.  My wife (God bless her) was the one that made me talk about the war and made me put up my medals.  I don't have them up to inflate my ego, but they're there because I'm proud of what I did and what my fellow soldiers did.  I'm tired of anyone that tries to create guilt of Vietnam.  I never felt it then and don't know.  All of us did what we had to do.  The veterans of this country didn't ask for parades or big parties, just the recognition we deserved as soldiers and sons of this country.  To all the guys out there go rent that 1946 movie, The Best Years of our Lives with Dana Andrews.  It's a story about the homecoming of 3 soldiers in 1945.  Compare that with how we got home.  Doc, if Nam vets today seem a little egotistical or too proud, we deserve that attitide.  Some of these vets are learning that we were good men in a bad war.  The arguments about killing (the types of it) and who did what, need to stop.  Those arguments died in 1972 with the protests.  We are here and now-gentlemen, Wear your medals, put those stickers in the window and don't be afraid to tell people your a vet.  If they can't deal with it, that's their problem.    
<p><code>--   (Prophet) </code><p>


